    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-01-14T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-01-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="720"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d720">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.113/1579</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by Mr. Joseph C. Green of the Division of Western
                        European Affairs of a Conversation With the First Secretary of the British
                        Embassy</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Wiggin</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-01-14">January 14,
                            1935</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>In compliance with the Under Secretary’s instructions, I requested Mr. Wiggin to
                    call at my office this morning. I handed him the note of January 10, addressed
                    to the British Ambassador in reply to the latter’s note No. 396 of December 12,
                        1934.<note n="43" xml:id="d720fn43">
                        <ref target="frus1934v03#pg_521">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1934, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, p. 521</ref>.</note> Mr. Wiggin read this
                    note with care. I then permitted him to read despatch No. 1056 of November [<hi
                        rend="italic">October</hi>] 24, 1934, from the Consul General in Hong
                        Kong.<note n="44" xml:id="d720fn44">
                        <ref target="frus1934v03#pg_513">
                            <hi rend="italic">Ibid</hi>., p. 513</ref>.</note> We discussed at some
                    length the Hong Kong regulations in respect to the transshipment and export of
                    arms, with special reference to the provisions of the Convention and Statute on
                    Freedom of Transit, signed at Barcelona on April 20, 1921.</p>
                <p>Mr. Wiggin said that it was obvious that the Hong Kong control of the arms
                    traffic to China needed to be stiffened and that the suggestion contained in the
                    penultimate paragraph of our note of January 10 was a very reasonable
                    suggestion.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>J[<hi rend="smallcaps">oseph</hi>] C. G[<hi rend="smallcaps"
                        >reen</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
